- Tue 30 Apr 2019. Strategy shift needed
[Express, abridged, edited]
https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1121155/ebola-outbreak-congo-world-health-organisation-pandemic-stratgey-shift
[Byline: Ciaran McGrath]

The ongoing Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) is "profoundly worrying," World Health Organisation director-general Dr. Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus has said during a visit to the country to assess the worsening situation following the brutal murder of a doctor who was treating victims of the killer virus.

Dr. Ghebreyesus visited the Butembo region, along with Dr. Matshidiso Moeti. It was in Butembo on 19 Apr 2019 that WHO epidemiologist Dr. Richard Mouzoko was killed by armed men while he and colleagues were working on the response to what is the 2nd-worst outbreak of Ebola in history. Dr. Ghebreyesus said: "Dr. Mouzoko's death moved me profoundly."

Dr. Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus: "I am also profoundly worried about the situation. Cases are increasing because of violent acts that set us back each time. We have already begun to adjust our response."

Dr. Ghebreyesus and Dr. Moeti urged the international community to step up support to contain the Ebola outbreak, including filling the funding gap that threatens to stymie the Ebola response. Most Ebola response activities, including community engagement, vaccination, and case investigation, have been relaunched following a slowdown in the wake of the attack that left Dr. Mouzoko dead and 2 people injured.

However, Dr. Ghebreyesus and Dr. Moeti voiced their deep concern that a rise in reported cases in recent weeks is straining resources even further.

